Author-Name: Hongbin Li 
Author-Name: Mark Rosenzweig 
Author-Name: Junsen Zhang 
Title: Altruism, Favoritism, and Guilt in the Allocation of Family Resources: Sophie's Choice in Mao's Mass Send-Down Movement 
Abstract:
 We use survey data on twins in urban China, among whom many experienced
 the consequences of the forced mass rustication movement of the Cultural
 Revolution, to identify the roles of altruism, favoritism, and guilt in
 affecting family behavior. We exploit the fact that many families were
 forced to select one of their adolescent children to be sent down. We show
 the conditions under which guilt, favoritism, and altruism can be
 identified using such data. We find that parents behaved altruistically,
 showed favoritism, but also exhibited guilt: the child experiencing more
 rustication years received higher parental transfers despite having higher
 earnings. (c) 2010 by The University of Chicago. All rights reserved. 
